metadata.name: High Spirits! #280
metadata.description:
There’s always a time and a place to let loose, sit back, and lift those spirits! Through the ages, images of the filled cup, mug, or cocktail glass have molded the way we envision relaxation and good times. They’ve encoded an escape, a panacea, a nostalgic refuge, and a feeling that we seek — but may not find. 

So instead, let’s stay in the moment and live sip by sip, here and now. Let’s look directly into the blazing neon lights, experience something unexpected, and remember that the best drink is one shared. Cheers to all!

--------

Many pieces of High Spirits! match the community-favorite cocktails shared in the Tender Discord’s #happyhour channel… others are timeless cocktails and mocktails, defined in bold headline. Still more outputs are generative mysteries, concocted from Mr. Kislev’s Kode, open to your inventive interpretations. Enjoy the eighties electric vibes and mid-century styling, print a poster, and trade for your favorites!

--------

TENDER x Orr Kislev
September 2022

It is an Image composition made using PureSpider's fxhash-php maker tool.

Made with Magicavoxel size 2048 x 2048

metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #126
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Paper Mandala #31
metadata.description:
A collaboration with P1xelboy and Paper Buddha.
Beautiful paper mandalas made purely with code in Paper Buddha's style.
Features include:
27 different palettes
3 different mandala types (Lotus, Starburst Style 1 and Starburst Style 2)
Four sections of the mandala with one of 10 different pattern types (Dots, Checks, Crosses, Triangles, Stripes, Circles, Polygons, Lazers, Quadrants and Hatching)
4 different direction types of shadow - of varying length
Randomly placed star background
Randomly placed Nebula
Possible Special Pattern Effect with darker stippling pattern
Possible Nirvana Effect where random colors are added to one of either Golden, Silver, Bronze, Blue Moon or Sea Green palettes.

Using only code, this produces a unique output which does take a few seconds to load.
Press "S" to Save your unique Paper Mandala as a 2048 x 2048 JPG
Press "R" for a random shuffle effect - (please wait for reload) - Refresh page to reset

The project works in a responsive browser, so to set up for phone background or watch, resize the browser accordingly and Alt + Print Screen to get an appropriately sized image.

Offered as a Dutch Auction, holders of the first 20 tokens (1-20) will receive additional benefits in the form of utility for future releases in the P1xelboy/Paper Mandala collaboration series. (exact details to be determined)
This utility will remain attached to tokens 1-20 and transfer to the new owner upon subsequent secondary sales.

Uses p5.js and p5.pattern
@p1x3lboy @paperbuddha - September 2022

metadata.name: Obliques #231
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Ari's Thread #116
metadata.description:
I side with the idea that we made this reality so weird merely to satisfy our -psychotic- need to overcomplicate things. Not you, of course.

That's why I believe that our choices don't "create our own path" but a maze for others to (try to) solve.
This God or that One or none, the old songs or the new ones, rooting for or against…
The deepest we meet into each other's maze, the more choices we share. Reciprocally, when we lack the interest to explore even a couple of turns, we're but a first impression to each other.

This work examines those ideas by continually presenting options to N individuals and then tracking their choices, which in turn generates different outputs at different depths.

To access them:
- press "S" for story mode, the sequence of choices
  - then, press "1" through "5" to change the speed
- press "L" for landscape, the first impression
- press "D" to see the details and view the mazes (may take a while)

metadata.name: Modern & Mundane #2
metadata.description:
In the modern times one works just enough to feel productive, and to escape the phenomenon that has recently introduced itself to humanity in excessive amounts - boredom.

And what do people do after work? They distract themselves. Distractions are all around us, completely pointless, completely useless, and very addictive. I'm not even going to list them, since I'm sure you can think of many by yourself. As Bertrand Russell wrote in his book <The Conquest of Happiness (1930)> - "All these devices give us illusions of meaningful engagements"

But, how does one solve the fear of boredom? Well, I actually got no clue.
And now that I think of it, do we really need to fix it?

metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #15
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Natt #88
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press “space” to pause the animation and “s” to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add “?pd=x” (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press “s” to save. Note, for higher values of “x” rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size. 


Generative artwork by Tengil, 2022.

For licenses see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt.

metadata.name: Out—Land #74
metadata.description:
Nowhere but here, before—a prequel, of sorts,
with nothing yet built to fall;
a jagged canvas,
unowned, unknown…
brutal even if naive

——

A : Animate rendering
S : Save at 2000x2500 pixels
1 -> 5 : Save 3000x3750 -> 7000x8750
(incrementing width 1000 pixels with each step)
